WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.500 --> 00:00:03.310
LESTER CHEN: Thanks
so much, Emily.

00:00:03.310 --> 00:00:06.160
So I will assure you all a
disclaimer that our slides

00:00:06.160 --> 00:00:09.910
won't be as graph-heavy as
Andreas', and we won't be

00:00:09.910 --> 00:00:13.060
talking about stage rollouts
and whatnot kind of like Emily,

00:00:13.060 --> 00:00:13.570
but--

00:00:13.570 --> 00:00:14.440
TIMOTHY EVANS: Over the head.

00:00:14.440 --> 00:00:15.565
LESTER CHEN: Over the head.

00:00:15.565 --> 00:00:17.860
But we're here talking
about content, and content

00:00:17.860 --> 00:00:19.360
as it relates to YouTube.

00:00:19.360 --> 00:00:22.360
And I'm on the YouTube end,
and who better to bring

00:00:22.360 --> 00:00:23.910
than a YouTuber himself?

00:00:23.910 --> 00:00:25.281
You're all the way from Boston.

00:00:25.281 --> 00:00:27.280
And we're be talking about
mobile gaming content

00:00:27.280 --> 00:00:29.590
and the rise of
how users have been

00:00:29.590 --> 00:00:34.420
consuming content on YouTube
around this category.

00:00:34.420 --> 00:00:36.810
So I'll do some slides.

00:00:36.810 --> 00:00:40.720
Let's see about where
mobile gaming has come from.

00:00:40.720 --> 00:00:44.380
So obviously a huge evolution
from linear puzzle games

00:00:44.380 --> 00:00:48.040
like a Tetris to all of a
sudden, a worldwide interactive

00:00:48.040 --> 00:00:50.471
[? PVP ?] game such
as Clash Royale.

00:00:50.471 --> 00:00:52.720
And when talking about these
kind of games and the way

00:00:52.720 --> 00:00:55.000
that content is
consumed, they obviously

00:00:55.000 --> 00:00:57.760
have very different
characteristics.

00:00:57.760 --> 00:01:00.650
Replayability,
iterative game modes,

00:01:00.650 --> 00:01:02.380
which gives folks
like Tim a lot more

00:01:02.380 --> 00:01:04.750
content to make
once a game is both

00:01:04.750 --> 00:01:09.200
launched and has DLC
coming out regularly.

00:01:09.200 --> 00:01:13.000
So mobile gaming on YouTube
has really seen a huge increase

00:01:13.000 --> 00:01:15.530
in the past two
years, as far as hours

00:01:15.530 --> 00:01:18.550
watched is a main metric
that we use at YouTube.

00:01:18.550 --> 00:01:23.150
Not so much views anymore,
more just total empirical hours

00:01:23.150 --> 00:01:26.290
or time watched has just
completely blown up.

00:01:26.290 --> 00:01:28.270
And I think games like
the Supercell games,

00:01:28.270 --> 00:01:31.420
Clash of Clans, Clash Royale,
games like Pokemon Go,

00:01:31.420 --> 00:01:33.400
which saw a huge
spike last year,

00:01:33.400 --> 00:01:36.640
and other games like Puzzles
and Dragons or Lineage or Angry

00:01:36.640 --> 00:01:40.750
Birds have really led to this
sudden increase on both content

00:01:40.750 --> 00:01:43.900
produced and content consumed.

00:01:43.900 --> 00:01:48.220
So this is just a brief timeline
of how watch time on YouTube

00:01:48.220 --> 00:01:52.540
has been really expanding
since all the way in 2015.

00:01:52.540 --> 00:01:55.539
So as you can see, the
launch of Clash Royale

00:01:55.539 --> 00:01:56.830
led to a little bit of a spike.

00:01:56.830 --> 00:02:00.610
And then last year Pokemon
was a phenomenal event

00:02:00.610 --> 00:02:04.690
that we've been tracking,
which led to a sudden peak.

00:02:04.690 --> 00:02:06.914
The slope is still
very much steady,

00:02:06.914 --> 00:02:08.830
and we see a steady
increase in the way people

00:02:08.830 --> 00:02:10.270
are consuming games.

00:02:10.270 --> 00:02:15.160
And it's really encouraging
to see creators also adopt

00:02:15.160 --> 00:02:16.900
mobile-first
strategies in the way

00:02:16.900 --> 00:02:19.840
that their channel
DNA is composed.

00:02:19.840 --> 00:02:22.120
So, Ash, to you.

00:02:22.120 --> 00:02:24.040
So I was kind of
doing some digging.

00:02:24.040 --> 00:02:25.810
TIMOTHY EVANS: Uh-oh.

00:02:25.810 --> 00:02:29.830
LESTER CHEN: And I think
September 2, almost three

00:02:29.830 --> 00:02:33.520
years ago, was the first time
that you really took a stab

00:02:33.520 --> 00:02:35.170
at uploading YouTube content.

00:02:35.170 --> 00:02:37.095
Can you tell me a
little bit about what

00:02:37.095 --> 00:02:39.220
was going through your head
when you were thinking,

00:02:39.220 --> 00:02:42.009
what is the first video before
hitting the Publish button?

00:02:42.009 --> 00:02:43.050
TIMOTHY EVANS: Sure, yes.

00:02:43.050 --> 00:02:45.190
So I had absolutely
no experience

00:02:45.190 --> 00:02:50.440
in a, mobile gaming, or
b, in YouTube, certainly.

00:02:50.440 --> 00:02:53.080
So I lacked the
technical expertise along

00:02:53.080 --> 00:02:55.180
with just the
networking that you

00:02:55.180 --> 00:02:57.010
would think one
should have if they

00:02:57.010 --> 00:03:00.684
want to endeavor to establish
a really good YouTube channel.

00:03:00.684 --> 00:03:03.100
So I didn't have any of that,
and I had really bad quality

00:03:03.100 --> 00:03:03.880
to boot.

00:03:03.880 --> 00:03:07.750
And I just uploaded a
few videos just for my--

00:03:07.750 --> 00:03:09.950
it was for Clash of
Clans at the time,

00:03:09.950 --> 00:03:13.090
and it was just for my guild,
my clan inside the game just

00:03:13.090 --> 00:03:15.005
to cover special events
that we were hosting.

00:03:15.005 --> 00:03:17.380
And now three years later,
I'm here on the stage with you

00:03:17.380 --> 00:03:17.830
somehow.

00:03:17.830 --> 00:03:19.663
I don't know how the
heck it happened, but--

00:03:19.663 --> 00:03:21.550
LESTER CHEN: So
obviously, like you said,

00:03:21.550 --> 00:03:23.680
your content started off--

00:03:23.680 --> 00:03:26.810
I'll be a dick here
and say it was rough.

00:03:26.810 --> 00:03:28.690
TIMOTHY EVANS: Yeah,
to say the least.

00:03:28.690 --> 00:03:30.940
LESTER CHEN: I was watching
it, and it was pretty bad.

00:03:30.940 --> 00:03:33.460
[LAUGHTER]

00:03:33.460 --> 00:03:34.335
And now--

00:03:34.335 --> 00:03:35.710
TIMOTHY EVANS:
What a great host.

00:03:35.710 --> 00:03:38.300
LESTER CHEN: Now, you have
a very beautiful intro.

00:03:38.300 --> 00:03:40.150
And clearly, I
think directionally,

00:03:40.150 --> 00:03:41.290
things have changed.

00:03:41.290 --> 00:03:44.410
But can you tell me what
has necessarily changed,

00:03:44.410 --> 00:03:45.355
both within the game?

00:03:47.801 --> 00:03:49.300
What's giving you
more encouragement

00:03:49.300 --> 00:03:50.304
to continue uploading?

00:03:50.304 --> 00:03:52.470
TIMOTHY EVANS: Yeah, so I
think you were being kind.

00:03:52.470 --> 00:03:53.720
It was absolutely awful.

00:03:53.720 --> 00:03:57.910
You can see I didn't even
utilize the full landscape

00:03:57.910 --> 00:03:58.720
mode.

00:03:58.720 --> 00:04:03.220
But I think that when
I started, I just

00:04:03.220 --> 00:04:06.780
wanted to do it purely
as a small little hobby.

00:04:06.780 --> 00:04:09.250
I didn't even think it was
possible for someone like me.

00:04:09.250 --> 00:04:11.170
When I started my YouTube
channel, I was 32.

00:04:11.170 --> 00:04:13.490
I was playing with
16-year-olds-- kind of creepy,

00:04:13.490 --> 00:04:14.110
I know.

00:04:14.110 --> 00:04:18.370
But I didn't think that I had
that infectious personality

00:04:18.370 --> 00:04:20.860
that could certainly
take off, so I just had--

00:04:20.860 --> 00:04:25.570
I set really, really
minimal goals for myself,

00:04:25.570 --> 00:04:27.130
just learning one
new thing a week

00:04:27.130 --> 00:04:29.020
and trying to apply
it to my channel,

00:04:29.020 --> 00:04:30.964
as I like to tackle
bigger things in life.

00:04:30.964 --> 00:04:32.380
No matter what
you're doing is try

00:04:32.380 --> 00:04:34.040
to continue to get better at it.

00:04:34.040 --> 00:04:40.570
So that led to not even
close to where I see myself

00:04:40.570 --> 00:04:41.950
right now as the final product.

00:04:41.950 --> 00:04:44.050
So I'm still kind of
continuing on those trends,

00:04:44.050 --> 00:04:45.647
but, yeah, just one
thing at a time.

00:04:45.647 --> 00:04:47.230
LESTER CHEN: And
you're up to-- what--

00:04:47.230 --> 00:04:48.260
like 500,000 subscribers?

00:04:48.260 --> 00:04:49.593
TIMOTHY EVANS: We're closing in.

00:04:49.593 --> 00:04:50.911
We're closing in, but yeah.

00:04:50.911 --> 00:04:51.410
Yeah.

00:04:51.410 --> 00:04:53.990
So certainly not the
biggest in the ecosystem,

00:04:53.990 --> 00:04:58.720
but just to inject a
little bit of pride,

00:04:58.720 --> 00:05:01.360
I've managed to do
it sticking to myself

00:05:01.360 --> 00:05:02.830
and not being
someone who I'm not,

00:05:02.830 --> 00:05:06.040
and covering more
strategic elements of games

00:05:06.040 --> 00:05:08.962
rather than being
a big personality.

00:05:08.962 --> 00:05:12.930
LESTER CHEN: So in your opinion,
there's obviously tons of--

00:05:12.930 --> 00:05:14.170
it's very subjective.

00:05:14.170 --> 00:05:17.260
Really, what makes good content,
and what did you find really?

00:05:17.260 --> 00:05:19.150
Did you stick to--
and I guess is

00:05:19.150 --> 00:05:20.620
this the game subject matter?

00:05:20.620 --> 00:05:23.410
Was this a certain format?

00:05:23.410 --> 00:05:26.590
What do you really define
as good content and content

00:05:26.590 --> 00:05:28.600
that your audience
really not only watched

00:05:28.600 --> 00:05:30.625
for the first time,
but continued watching?

00:05:30.625 --> 00:05:32.250
TIMOTHY EVANS: Yeah,
so it's definitely

00:05:32.250 --> 00:05:35.034
different for every individual,
and every content creator,

00:05:35.034 --> 00:05:36.700
and every developer
what kind of content

00:05:36.700 --> 00:05:38.560
you're looking for your game.

00:05:38.560 --> 00:05:40.390
But for me, I've
always just strived

00:05:40.390 --> 00:05:42.430
to make content that
I would want to watch.

00:05:42.430 --> 00:05:44.872
Really basic and
cliche, but I just

00:05:44.872 --> 00:05:47.080
think it takes a lot of grit
when you're starting out

00:05:47.080 --> 00:05:49.330
in YouTube just as you're
starting out as a game

00:05:49.330 --> 00:05:52.359
developer where you're
not going to experience--

00:05:52.359 --> 00:05:54.400
as much as people like to
believe their channel's

00:05:54.400 --> 00:05:56.170
going to blow up one
day and they're just

00:05:56.170 --> 00:05:58.880
going to be a millionaire, it
just doesn't work like that.

00:05:58.880 --> 00:06:00.940
You have to get through
that first year,

00:06:00.940 --> 00:06:04.720
or even more sometimes, of
seeing stagnant, if any,

00:06:04.720 --> 00:06:05.630
growth.

00:06:05.630 --> 00:06:08.050
So what I think makes
good content is being

00:06:08.050 --> 00:06:11.710
true to yourself,
and, at the same time,

00:06:11.710 --> 00:06:15.850
not being afraid to be
transparent, and also

00:06:15.850 --> 00:06:16.540
be honest.

00:06:16.540 --> 00:06:19.365
So I've always built
my channel around--

00:06:19.365 --> 00:06:20.740
even if I have
good relationships

00:06:20.740 --> 00:06:23.270
with all the developers
that I work with,

00:06:23.270 --> 00:06:24.640
I think that I'm honest.

00:06:24.640 --> 00:06:28.100
And I really love opinion
pieces, if you will.

00:06:28.100 --> 00:06:30.970
So I just think making your
content worth watching,

00:06:30.970 --> 00:06:34.960
no matter what that
vehicle is to get it there,

00:06:34.960 --> 00:06:36.820
is really important.

00:06:36.820 --> 00:06:39.130
How do you differentiate
yourself from everybody

00:06:39.130 --> 00:06:42.610
out there making content
on the same games?

00:06:42.610 --> 00:06:45.340
So I think being a little bit
m but staying true to yourself,

00:06:45.340 --> 00:06:48.592
working within your
personality, to make content.

00:06:48.592 --> 00:06:50.050
LESTER CHEN:
Something I've noticed

00:06:50.050 --> 00:06:52.990
is some of these
top grossing games

00:06:52.990 --> 00:06:56.950
oftentimes don't have any
or very low viewership

00:06:56.950 --> 00:06:58.970
on the YouTube platform.

00:06:58.970 --> 00:07:00.940
Do you have any kind of
intuition or hypothesis

00:07:00.940 --> 00:07:01.600
around that?

00:07:01.600 --> 00:07:05.380
Games that a ton of people
play, and spend, and clearly

00:07:05.380 --> 00:07:07.990
come back after the first
try, but they really

00:07:07.990 --> 00:07:09.880
aren't watching any
kind of content.

00:07:09.880 --> 00:07:12.670
What are some things you
really think lead to that

00:07:12.670 --> 00:07:14.545
or some of the problems there?

00:07:14.545 --> 00:07:17.320
TIMOTHY EVANS: Yeah, so the
developers that I work with

00:07:17.320 --> 00:07:21.940
have really valued community
almost to its detriment

00:07:21.940 --> 00:07:24.580
at some times, but it
pays off in the long term.

00:07:24.580 --> 00:07:27.490
Some developers are
lucky enough to have

00:07:27.490 --> 00:07:30.640
billions of marketing
dollars, if not hundreds

00:07:30.640 --> 00:07:32.080
of millions or millions.

00:07:32.080 --> 00:07:34.169
And those type of
games, in my opinion,

00:07:34.169 --> 00:07:35.710
no matter what they
do, they're going

00:07:35.710 --> 00:07:37.570
to succeed because they're
throwing so much money.

00:07:37.570 --> 00:07:39.400
Like Mobile Strike--
no offense if Mobile

00:07:39.400 --> 00:07:40.750
Strike's developer's here--

00:07:40.750 --> 00:07:42.947
but if you throw
millions and millions

00:07:42.947 --> 00:07:44.530
and millions of
dollars into the game,

00:07:44.530 --> 00:07:46.238
of course you're going
to generate users,

00:07:46.238 --> 00:07:49.510
thus rank high on
the app store, thus

00:07:49.510 --> 00:07:51.710
continue to get that momentum.

00:07:51.710 --> 00:07:55.510
But I think that what a
lot of developers miss

00:07:55.510 --> 00:07:58.930
is how to use content
creators strategically

00:07:58.930 --> 00:08:01.819
to grow that ecosystem
around their game.

00:08:01.819 --> 00:08:04.110
And I think they do it in
the wrong way a lot of times.

00:08:04.110 --> 00:08:05.530
I'm sure we'll talk
more about in a bit.

00:08:05.530 --> 00:08:06.530
LESTER CHEN: Yeah, yeah.

00:08:06.530 --> 00:08:08.730
Well, you talked briefly
on the detriment sometimes

00:08:08.730 --> 00:08:10.570
of growing community.

00:08:10.570 --> 00:08:13.600
I have to guess negative
feedback and kids

00:08:13.600 --> 00:08:15.060
on Facebook saying, yeah.

00:08:15.060 --> 00:08:15.850
TIMOTHY EVANS: Which can
be good though, yeah.

00:08:15.850 --> 00:08:16.630
Yeah, so the games
I cover, I mean,

00:08:16.630 --> 00:08:18.421
they can't put out a
tweet about their game

00:08:18.421 --> 00:08:20.500
without getting the top
tweets, your game sucks.

00:08:20.500 --> 00:08:21.470
It's dying, whatever.

00:08:21.470 --> 00:08:23.470
But that's a good thing
because people are still

00:08:23.470 --> 00:08:24.460
passionate about it.

00:08:24.460 --> 00:08:26.110
It's better than sending
out a tweet about your game

00:08:26.110 --> 00:08:27.568
and getting absolutely
no response.

00:08:27.568 --> 00:08:28.780
LESTER CHEN: Right.

00:08:28.780 --> 00:08:31.420
So I want to touch on the
nuances right of capturing

00:08:31.420 --> 00:08:32.559
mobile content.

00:08:32.559 --> 00:08:34.839
I come from the
PC console world,

00:08:34.839 --> 00:08:36.880
so I think the path was
a little bit clearer when

00:08:36.880 --> 00:08:39.549
certain hardware like
capture cards were released,

00:08:39.549 --> 00:08:41.750
and encoding
software, and the way

00:08:41.750 --> 00:08:44.900
to just to record both like
VOD content and live streams,

00:08:44.900 --> 00:08:47.350
it was a lot more
commonly known.

00:08:47.350 --> 00:08:50.359
But when it comes to mobile
content and how you capture it,

00:08:50.359 --> 00:08:52.150
can you talk a little
bit about your set-up

00:08:52.150 --> 00:08:54.316
and maybe some of the nuances
of how you can capture

00:08:54.316 --> 00:08:57.340
from a device or from
your tablet or phone,

00:08:57.340 --> 00:08:59.147
and how you actually
eventually get

00:08:59.147 --> 00:09:01.480
the video content that you're
recording to your computer

00:09:01.480 --> 00:09:02.260
and up on YouTube?

00:09:02.260 --> 00:09:03.093
TIMOTHY EVANS: Sure.

00:09:03.093 --> 00:09:06.760
I think this is a hurdle that's
becoming easier and easier

00:09:06.760 --> 00:09:09.310
to clear with technology
moving in the direction

00:09:09.310 --> 00:09:11.200
where you can easily
record your device.

00:09:11.200 --> 00:09:13.870
However, I think it's really
paramount for developers

00:09:13.870 --> 00:09:19.090
to work with content creators to
help increase their production

00:09:19.090 --> 00:09:19.780
value.

00:09:19.780 --> 00:09:22.360
And you can record right
from your screen now

00:09:22.360 --> 00:09:24.970
with a lot of different apps,
a lot of mirror-type apps.

00:09:24.970 --> 00:09:28.630
Me, personally, I use a
hardware called Delgado,

00:09:28.630 --> 00:09:31.227
where you can just use a
lightning cable or HDMI cable

00:09:31.227 --> 00:09:32.560
and just hook right up directly.

00:09:32.560 --> 00:09:35.440
So there's a lot of ways to
do it, even with emulators.

00:09:35.440 --> 00:09:38.980
But it's up to basically try
to find the highest quality

00:09:38.980 --> 00:09:41.200
way that you can possibly
a, understand, and b,

00:09:41.200 --> 00:09:41.784
afford to use.

00:09:41.784 --> 00:09:44.366
LESTER CHEN: Well, I think it's
ironic because a lot of people

00:09:44.366 --> 00:09:46.790
are consuming the mobile
game content on their phones.

00:09:46.790 --> 00:09:48.220
But the broadcasters,
you're still

00:09:48.220 --> 00:09:51.839
pretty much wired to a very
static kind of set-up, right?

00:09:51.839 --> 00:09:53.005
TIMOTHY EVANS: Indeed, yeah.

00:09:53.005 --> 00:09:56.080
LESTER CHEN: Until Wi-Fi
capabilities and some things

00:09:56.080 --> 00:09:59.870
might be able to shift, or
storage space even on a phone,

00:09:59.870 --> 00:10:02.627
you're still kind of locked
to a very static set-up.

00:10:02.627 --> 00:10:03.460
TIMOTHY EVANS: Yeah.

00:10:03.460 --> 00:10:04.170
Yeah, it's true.

00:10:04.170 --> 00:10:05.690
And I think that
hopefully, we'll kind of

00:10:05.690 --> 00:10:06.856
move in the right direction.

00:10:06.856 --> 00:10:09.100
But yeah, that's kind of
where it is right now.

00:10:09.100 --> 00:10:11.420
LESTER CHEN: So let's
talk about ways developers

00:10:11.420 --> 00:10:14.090
have embraced YouTubers,
like going left to right.

00:10:14.090 --> 00:10:16.670
Someone like the largest
YouTube creator PewDiePie

00:10:16.670 --> 00:10:19.850
had worked with a developer
in order to make his own game.

00:10:19.850 --> 00:10:24.830
I think Supercell does quite
a good job using their talent

00:10:24.830 --> 00:10:29.870
as beacons to both announce game
mode launches, or new cards,

00:10:29.870 --> 00:10:32.150
or anything else
going on, and then

00:10:32.150 --> 00:10:35.000
Best Fiend's model, where
YouTubers and influencers are

00:10:35.000 --> 00:10:37.220
actually built into the games.

00:10:37.220 --> 00:10:41.450
In your experience,
what have you seen,

00:10:41.450 --> 00:10:43.400
or what are your best
practices or ways

00:10:43.400 --> 00:10:45.970
that developers have
used both you and some

00:10:45.970 --> 00:10:47.420
of the community in the space?

00:10:47.420 --> 00:10:49.715
And what is good,
and what is bad?

